{"title_page": "Amir Bhatia, Baron Bhatia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]  \n| name = The Lord Bhatia\n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] \n|image = Official portrait of Lord Bhatia crop 2.jpg\n|caption = Lord Bhatia in 2019\n|office1          = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start1      = 5 June 2001<br/>[[Life Peerage]]\n| birth_name = Amirali Alibhai Bhatia\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1932|03|18}} \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Non-affiliated members of the House of Lords|Non-affiliated]]\n| otherparty      = [[Crossbench]] (until 2010)\n}}\n'''Amirali Alibhai \"Amir\" Bhatia, Baron Bhatia''', [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] (born 18 March 1932) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] businessman and politician.\n\n==Background==\nAn [[Ismaili]] [[Muslim]] born in [[East Africa]], Bhatia was educated in schools in [[Tanzania]] and [[India]]. He is married to Nurnamu Amersi and has three daughters. He moved to the United Kingdom in 1972.\n\n==Career==\nBhatia was chairman and managing director of [[Forbes Campbell International]] Ltd between 1980 and 2001. He was the co-founder of the [[Ethnic Minority Foundation]] and its chair until 2009, and also helped establish the Council of Ethnic Minority Voluntary Sector Organisations (CEMVO). He is additionally a former trustee of various charitable organisations, including the [[National Lottery (United Kingdom)|National Lottery]] Charities Board and [[Oxfam]], serving as chairman of Oxfam Trading.\n\nIn 2006 he was the chair of the [[British Edutrust]] foundation, the organisation planning to sponsor [[Rhodesway School]]. He stepped down from the post in March 2009.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.edutrust.org/news/news+from+Edutrust/2009-03-13/New+board+and+management+arrangements+at+EACT\n|title=New board and management arrangements at EACT}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nBhatia was appointed an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[1997 Birthday Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=54794 |date=14 June 1997 |page=10 |supp=y}}</ref> On 5 June 2001, he was created a [[life peer]] as '''Baron Bhatia''', ''of [[Hampton, London|Hampton]] in the [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]'',<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=56232 |date=13 June 2001 |page=6953}}</ref> one of the first '[[people's peers]]'. He took his seat in the [[House of Lords]] as a [[crossbencher]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://members.parliament.uk/member/2165/career|title=Parliamentary career for Lord Bhatia|website=UK Parliament|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 Lord Bhatia received the Beacon Fellowship Prize for his leadership role in countering social deprivation and exclusion in the UK and internationally.<ref>[http://www.beaconfellowship.org.uk/press_releases.asp?rel=1029 Lord Bhatia \u2013 The Beacon Prize for Leadership], Beacon Fellowship. Retrieved 2 February 2012.</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn October 2010 Lord Bhatia was suspended for 8 months from the House of Lords due to the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal]].<ref name=\"bbc-20101021\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-11597922 |title=Three peers suspended from Lords over expenses claims |publisher=BBC |date=21 October 2010 |accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref> After this, Lord Batia sits in the House of Lords as a [[Non-affiliated members of the House of Lords|non-affiliated member]].\n\nIn December 2013, [[BBC Newsnight]] reported that Lord Bhatia had been accused by the Ethnic Minority Foundation of misappropriating \u00a3600,000 from the charity. Lord Bhatia is suing the charity for unfair dismissal, and his lawyers say that these allegations are confusing the historical position with the present dispute.<ref name=\"bbc-20131204\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25188606 |title=Lord Bhatia 'misappropriated 600,000 of charity funds' |author=Mark Daly |publisher=BBC |date=4 December 2013 |accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6727708.ece Millionaire Lord Bhatia claimed \u00a320,000 on small flat]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/8071615/Expenses-Baroness-Uddin-Lord-Bhatia-Lord-Paul-ordered-to-repay-200000.html Expenses: Baroness Uddin, Lord Bhatia, Lord Paul ordered to repay \u00a3200,000]\n* [http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2010/10/prileges-committee-report-on-conduct/ Conduct of Lord Bhatia, Lord Paul and Baroness Uddin]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhatia, Amir}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers]]\n[[Category:People's peers]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:British politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Tanzanian emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British Ismailis]]\n\n\n{{UK-politician-stub}}\n{{life-peer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]  \n| name = The Lord Bhatia\n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] \n|image = Official portrait of Lord Bhatia crop 3.jpg\n|caption = Lord Bhatia in 2019\n|office1          = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start1      = 5 June 2001<br/>[[Life Peerage]]\n| birth_name = Amirali Alibhai Bhatia\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1932|03|18}} \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Non-affiliated members of the House of Lords|Non-affiliated]]\n| otherparty      = [[Crossbench]] (until 2010)\n}}\n'''Amirali Alibhai \"Amir\" Bhatia, Baron Bhatia''', [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] (born 18 March 1932) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] businessman and politician.\n\n==Background==\nAn [[Ismaili]] [[Muslim]] born in [[East Africa]], Bhatia was educated in schools in [[Tanzania]] and [[India]]. He is married to Nurnamu Amersi and has three daughters. He moved to the United Kingdom in 1972.\n\n==Career==\nBhatia was chairman and managing director of [[Forbes Campbell International]] Ltd between 1980 and 2001. He was the co-founder of the [[Ethnic Minority Foundation]] and its chair until 2009, and also helped establish the Council of Ethnic Minority Voluntary Sector Organisations (CEMVO). He is additionally a former trustee of various charitable organisations, including the [[National Lottery (United Kingdom)|National Lottery]] Charities Board and [[Oxfam]], serving as chairman of Oxfam Trading.\n\nIn 2006 he was the chair of the [[British Edutrust]] foundation, the organisation planning to sponsor [[Rhodesway School]]. He stepped down from the post in March 2009.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.edutrust.org/news/news+from+Edutrust/2009-03-13/New+board+and+management+arrangements+at+EACT\n|title=New board and management arrangements at EACT}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nBhatia was appointed an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[1997 Birthday Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=54794 |date=14 June 1997 |page=10 |supp=y}}</ref> On 5 June 2001, he was created a [[life peer]] as '''Baron Bhatia''', ''of [[Hampton, London|Hampton]] in the [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]'',<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=56232 |date=13 June 2001 |page=6953}}</ref> one of the first '[[people's peers]]'. He took his seat in the [[House of Lords]] as a [[crossbencher]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://members.parliament.uk/member/2165/career|title=Parliamentary career for Lord Bhatia|website=UK Parliament|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 Lord Bhatia received the Beacon Fellowship Prize for his leadership role in countering social deprivation and exclusion in the UK and internationally.<ref>[http://www.beaconfellowship.org.uk/press_releases.asp?rel=1029 Lord Bhatia \u2013 The Beacon Prize for Leadership], Beacon Fellowship. Retrieved 2 February 2012.</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn October 2010 Lord Bhatia was suspended for 8 months from the House of Lords due to the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal]].<ref name=\"bbc-20101021\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-11597922 |title=Three peers suspended from Lords over expenses claims |publisher=BBC |date=21 October 2010 |accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref> After this, Lord Batia sits in the House of Lords as a [[Non-affiliated members of the House of Lords|non-affiliated member]].\n\nIn December 2013, [[BBC Newsnight]] reported that Lord Bhatia had been accused by the Ethnic Minority Foundation of misappropriating \u00a3600,000 from the charity. Lord Bhatia is suing the charity for unfair dismissal, and his lawyers say that these allegations are confusing the historical position with the present dispute.<ref name=\"bbc-20131204\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25188606 |title=Lord Bhatia 'misappropriated 600,000 of charity funds' |author=Mark Daly |publisher=BBC |date=4 December 2013 |accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6727708.ece Millionaire Lord Bhatia claimed \u00a320,000 on small flat]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/8071615/Expenses-Baroness-Uddin-Lord-Bhatia-Lord-Paul-ordered-to-repay-200000.html Expenses: Baroness Uddin, Lord Bhatia, Lord Paul ordered to repay \u00a3200,000]\n* [http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2010/10/prileges-committee-report-on-conduct/ Conduct of Lord Bhatia, Lord Paul and Baroness Uddin]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhatia, Amir}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers]]\n[[Category:People's peers]]\n